Les partisans
comments: On May 30, 1943, Joseph Kessel spent what was likely a wet Sunday afternoon with his nephew Maurice Druon at the Ashdown Park Hotel in Coulsdon, Surrey, drafting the lyrics to accompany Marly’s melody of "La chant des partisans". The next day the song was recorded for the first time by radio star Germaine Sablon at the Ealing Studios in West-London for tis film. The song would be broadcast by the BBC throughout the summer of 1944, as it became an anthem of Liberation.
